<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-24 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Grants Pardon to Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Three Israeli convicts,
involved in a daring escape bid from police custody, were
granted a presidential pardon, less than three months into their
sentence.
</P>
<P>
Confirming their release today, George Anastasiades, the
director of the central prison, said a total of 13 prisoners of
various nationalities had been granted pardon.
</P>
<P>
Some of them, including the three Israelis (David Biton, 24,
Shimon Amor, 28, and Avi Biton, 21,) have already left for their
countries, he said. But he declined to say when they were freed.
</P>
<P>
David Biton and Amor were sentenced last November 6 to
four years' imprisonment for planning and helping to free their
compatriots Shuki Samana, 24, and Avi Biton from police custody
last September in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Samana and Avi Biton were being transferred in a police car
to the Larnaca district court to face counterfeit charges, when
David Biton and Amor intercepted the vehicle with rented
motorbikes and at gun point they freed the two men.
</P>
<P>
All the four Israelis escaped and crossed the U.N. buffer zone
into the Turkish-controlled part of Nicosia but later, the same
day, they were handed over to the Cypriot police via the
U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Samana walked free after the trial while Avi Biton was
sentenced by the Larnaca court to 30 months' imprisonment for
possessing and exchanging fake U.S. bills in the southern
coastal resort of Ayia Napa.
</P>
<P>
Under Cyprus' constitution, only the president of the
Republic has the power to grant pardons, following
recommendations from the attorney-general.
</P>
<P>
The three men were the only Israelis at the prison, which
also houses around 150 Arab convicts, according to the prison
director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
