<HEADLINE> France Condemns Participation in Mercenaries in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 24 (Xinhua) -- France today condemned any
participation by Frenchmen in the reported mercenary force in
Zaire, and again denied any link between the French government and
such mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said
France does not have any military cooperation with Zaire and Paris
observes "very strictly" the arms embargo imposed by the European
Union on Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The French daily, Liberation, reported today that 280 European
mercenaries, including Frenchmen and led by Belgian Christian
Tavernier, are fighting for the Zairean government against Tutsi
rebels in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"I am formal. There're only five French military men present in
Zaire. France respects very strictly the arms embargo of the
European Union," said the spokesman, referring to the French
military attache and four French paramilitary policemen at the
French embassy in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"If it was confirmed to be exact, as certain media have
indicated, that the French nationals were acting under private
terms as mercenaries in Zaire, such actions could not but be
condemned in the clearest way because they do not square with the
policy of France," said the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
