<HEADLINE> Relief For Quake Victims in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Seismologists and soldiers in
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have been sent to Jiashi
County, which was rocked by a strong earthquakes Tuesday, to join
in rescue work there.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measuring 6.4 on the Richter Scale, killed at least
12 people and injured more than 40, causing a great deal of
property damage.
</P>
<P>
A team of 11 seismologists from the Xinjiang Seismological
Bureau flew 1,500 kilometers from Urumqi to the quake-stricken
area on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Setting up headquarters in a small hotel, they rigged a direct
phone line to send in data on the quakes information about the
devastated county. They warned that there could be a number of
aftershocks measuring more than five on the Richter scale, and
local authorities evacuated people from houses considered unsafe.
</P>
<P>
There was no report of new casualties, even though there have
been more than 400 aftershocks in the past several days, more than
20 of which were above four on the Richter Scale.
</P>
<P>
PLA soldiers and armed police stationed in Xinjiang went to
Jiashi and other quake-affected areas to help with rescue and
relief work. They have donated more than 20,000 yuan (about 2,400
US dollars) in relief funds and over 600 items of clothing, and
transported over 100 tons of relief materials to the
quake-stricken areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
