<HEADLINE> Philippine Vice President Eyes Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Although the presidential
election in the Philippines is still 18 months away, Vice
President Joseph Estrada officially launched his bid for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here today, Estrada's Party of the Filipino Masses
and Senate President Ernesto Maceda's National People's Coalition
jointly nominated the vice president as the candidate for
president.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches at the meeting, Estrada and Maceda appealed
to voters in the country to show their support to Estrada in next
year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Candidates are prohibited by law from campaigning until three
months before the election, which will be held in May 1998.
However, unofficial political maneuvering began in the country
last year.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos' ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union of
Christian Democrats) has not nominated its candidate, but as a
ruling party member, Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose
de Venecia has proclaimed his intention to run for the office.
</P>
<P>
It was reported however that Defense Secretary Renato de Villa
would join the ruling party and is likely to be chosen as the
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, the president serves a
single six-year term and is not allowed to seek re-election.
</P>
</TEXT>
