<HEADLINE> Cambodian Second Prime Minister's Party Refuses Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen said today that his Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) will not join a new alliance headed by the Funcinpec Party.
</P>
<P>
He said his party would not accept an invitation to join the
National United Front (NUF), but would want to continue working
with the Funcinpec of First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh in
both government and parliament.
</P>
<P>
As the CPP's vice chairman, Hun Sen made the announcement when
answering reporters' questions during a break at the opening
session of the CPP's annual congress.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to join with any front," Hun Sen said. "We
will not form any front, but we will cooperate with any political
party if necessary.
</P>
<P>
"It is not necessary to join an alliance because we have a
constitution which allows all political parties to live together
in society," he added.
</P>
<P>
The NUF is a new political alliance formed by the Funcinpec
Party in a bid to run for local elections later this year and
national elections in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Its charter has been approved by the Funcinpec Party, the Khmer
Nation Party led by former finance minister Sam Rainsy and the
Democratic National Union Movement.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh told reporters on Thursday that he would go
personally to present the front's charter to CPP Chairman Chea Sim
and see "if the CPP is able to join."
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said the front is "not an alliance against this or
that" and is open to all including the CPP.
</P>
<P>
If the CPP refuses to join, the front will go ahead alone to
run for the upcoming elections, Ranariddh added.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec and the CPP, the two largest parties in the National
Assembly, formed an alliance after U.N.-sponsored elections in
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
