<HEADLINE> Chinese Party Leader Speaks On Multi-Party Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, a member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) Central Committee, told a group of officials today
that the role of China's non-communist parties to supervise over
the CPC should be enhanced and improved in the multi-party
cooperation system.
</P>
<P>
Li, also chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference, made the remarks at
commencement services for a class on the united front and
multi-party cooperation for senior officials at the provincial or
ministry level.
</P>
<P>
Li said that, since China launched its reforms and opening up
drive, the scientific and cultural level of Chinese officials has
greatly improved, and that should be regarded as a major
achievement in the country's effort to produce more qualified
officials.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, while there is a great deal of knowledge
about the natural sciences, some officials fall rather short when
it comes to comprehensive social knowledge.
</P>
<P>
"Some comrades don't even have an adequate understanding of
some common knowledge in the social sciences and of fundamental
theories of Marxism," he remarked.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that officials, especially senior ones, find
it impossible to observe and understand the world's development,
and to find solutions to a range of complicated problems if they
know little about Marxism and other areas of the social sciences.
</P>
<P>
"The central leadership of the Party with comrade Jiang Zemin
at the core have always placed great importance on studying the
social sciences, and have tried to set a good example for the
whole Party in this respect," he said, and called on all
officials, including those from non-communist parties, to strive
to improve their knowledge and understanding of Marxism.
</P>
<P>
In referring to the principle of "long-term co-existence and
mutual supervision" for China's multi-party cooperation system, he
said it reflects the intimate relations between the CPC and the
non-communist democratic parties, which have the same basic
interests.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China's reforms, opening-up, and
modernization drive need the CPC to set up various supervisory
systems, including supervision from non-communist parties.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized that supervision of non-communist parties
must be conducted with the idea of helping improve and strengthen
the CPC leadership instead of negating or weakening it.
</P>
<P>
"The CPC and democratic parties are friendly parties working
side by side for China's prosperity, democracy, and socialist
ethical and cultural development. Their relationship is not one
of a leading party and oppositional parties," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
