<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No EU Expansion Until Early Next Century: Dutch Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Dutch State Secretary of
Foreign Affairs Michiel Patijn said today that the European Union
(EU) will not take in new members until early next century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing ambassadors of Central European countries at a
conference in The Hague, Patijn said membership negotiations would
start six months after the Inter-Governmental Conference (IGC) on
a new EU treaty finishes in the summer.
</P>
<P>
"The Netherlands wants the IGC to be rounded off in Amsterdam
in June, so that the political decisions on expansion can be taken
at the EU Luxembourg summit at the end of the year," the state
secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands currently holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the European Commission (EC) made its prediction
that the 15-member bloc would not be enlarged until the start of
the next century, sparking serious concern among the Eastern
European countries most likely to join the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Later, the EC corrected the statement by saying new accessions
could be realized any time.
</P>
<P>
The EC has already said that, shortly after the conclusion of
the IGC, it would be presenting its proposals on enlargement and
draw up an advisory report for each candidate country, as well as
an overall strategy.
</P>
<P>
No negotiations will be conducted on enlargement during the
half-year Dutch EU presidency which started on January 1, although
Patijn noted that the time would need to be used in order to
identify potential complications in advance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
