<HEADLINE> Japan's Government Bonds Could Top 400 Trillion Yen in 2005 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Finance Ministry
warned today that outstanding government bonds could top 400
trillion yen (about 3.45 trillion U.S. dollars) by fiscal 2005 if
the government fails to cut spending.
</P>
<P>
A ministry report submitted to the Budget Committee in the
House of Representatives says the government will face an
estimated revenue shortfall of more than 4 trillion yen (34.5
billion dollars) in fiscal 1998 due to debt-servicing and other
spending increases.
</P>
<P>
The report recommends government expenditure be thoroughly
reviewed to restore Japan's fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
Kyodo news service reported that the ministry has mapped out a
medium-term fiscal outlook following the adoption of a plan late
last year by the cabinet to end the government's reliance on
deficit-covering bonds to cover revenue shortfalls by the end of
fiscal 2005.
</P>
<P>
The report offers two scenarios on the assumption that
deficit-financing government bonds, of which 7.47 trillion yen
(64.85 billion dollars) are planned to be issued in fiscal 1997,
will be annually reduced by 1 trillion yen (8.65 billion dollars)
over eight years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Squeezes Alcohol Industry to Boost Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The cash-starved Ukrainian
government is targeting the alcohol industry to increase state
revenues by raising taxes, setting mandatory prices and sending
tax inspectors to distilleries to crack down on black marketeering.
</P>
<P>
Deputy prime minister Viktor Pinzenik justified the moves,
saying that it was understandable for the government to collect
high taxes because the production cost of Ukrainian vodka is very
low.
</P>
<P>
The government issued a decree early this month, banning sales
of all alcohol except beer in spaces smaller than 20 square
meters. The move was aimed at boosting revenue by bringing all
alcohol sales into larger stores that are easier to regulate.
</P>
<P>
But thousands of roadside kiosks across the country still sell
all sorts of alcohol, including imported beer and liquor. They
often buy and sell illegally produced alcohol to avoid paying tax.
</P>
<P>
The government is also trying to weed out illegal producers and
smugglers of alcohol who accounted for more than half the 320
million liters of alcohol sold in the country last year.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet republic wants set minimum prices for alcohol
to stop illegal sales at low prices and ensure a level playing
field for legal producers.
</P>
<P>
Leonid Svatkov, president of the National Food Industry
Committee, said legal producers would not be forced to raise
prices.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the task of forcing illegal producers to
surrender would be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
Legal producers are also planning to undercut their illegal
competitors and force them out of the market.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has tried to crack down on cross-border
smuggling, one of the main sources of illegal alcohol, it is still
a thriving business along Ukraine's 4,650-kilometer border which
is difficult to police.
</P>
<P>
Pinzenik said border guards will get bonuses equaling the value
of their haul if they confiscate smuggled goods.
</P>
<P>
The government estimates half of the production from legal
distilleries finds its way onto the black market. So it has now
decided to follow Russia's lead and send tax inspectors into
Ukraine's distilleries to make sure that all alcohol going out of
the factory gate is subjected to tax.
</P>
<P>
After Russia introduced tax inspectors last year, its legal
alcohol industry imposed huge price hikes which led many producers
to the brink of collapse. Economic experts fear the same thing
could happen in Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNECE Lists 15 Preliminary POPs to Be Included </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Europe published here today an initial list of 15
persistent organic pollutants (POPs) after a five-day meeting of
the UNECE working group on strategies.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached a decisive stage in the drawing up of a
protocol on persistent organic pollutants (POPs)," said Lars
Nordberg, deputy director of the UNECE environment and human
settlements division.
</P>
<P>
"It has not been easy to draw up an initial list of POPs for
inclusion in a protocol because so many interests are at stake,"
he noted, adding that some POPs are useful for agriculture and
even for human health although they are generally harmful to human
beings.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are going on to have a new protocol to the
Convention on Long-Range Transboundary Air Pollution signed in
Geneva in 1979 under UNECE auspices.
</P>
<P>
The 15 POPs, which may be included in the draft protocol on
POPs, are aldrin, chlordane, chlordecone, DDT (DDD and DDE),
dieldrin, dioxins (OCDDs), furans (PCDFs), endrin, heptachlor,
hexabromobiphenyl, hexachlorobenzene, mirex, PAHs, PCBs, and
toxaphene.
</P>
<P>
Short-chain chlorinated paraffins, lindane and
pentachlorophenol will require further examination before a
decision can be taken about their possible inclusion.
</P>
<P>
POPs are divided into three categories: industrial chemicals,
by-products or contaminants, and pesticides. Their concentrations
increase in fatty tissues.
</P>
<P>
In its press release, the UNECE gave an example to explain how
POPs gradually build up in the food chain. Although the
concentrations of a substance such as PCBs or DDT deposited into a
lake may be very low, they will be concentrated in the fatty
tissues of plankton living in the lake. Fish feeding on the
plankton will further concentrate the PCBs or DDT. This process
will be repeated in fish-eating birds, mammals and humans.
</P>
<P>
Very high concentrations of these substances have long been
associated with a number of carcinogenic and other health effects.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, however, there has been a growing body of
information showing that much more subtle effects can occur at
environmental concentrations which may be a result of long-range
transboundary air deposition. Some of these health effects are
immune suppression, intellectual impairment and birth defects.
</P>
<P>
"That is the reason for the development of the protocol," said
Nordberg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
