<HEADLINE> Cohen Sworn In as U.S. Defense Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Sen. William
Cohen of Maine was sworn in as the nation's defense secretary
today, the first and only Republican in Bill Clinton's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who was confirmed by the Senate's 99-0 vote Wednesday,
took the oath from Vice President Al Gore in the Oval Office with
President Clinton standing behind him.
</P>
<P>
Clinton chose the Republican to join his cabinet to show his
willingness of cooperation with the Republican-led Congress. Cohen
told Clinton he looks forward to "serving you on a bipartisan
team, to a new century with clarity of purpose."
</P>
<P>
In his confirmation hearings, Cohen told the Senate Armed
Services Committee that he would continue to carry out Clinton's
policies to build partnership with Russia, set NATO on the course
toward enlargement and put focus on relations with Asia and the
Pacific. He also stressed the necessity for modernization of the
U.S. weaponry to preserve a high-quality force.
</P>
<P>
He said one of his top priorities will be to go to Europe and
make it clear to America's friends that the U.S. troops in Bosnia
will be withdrawn by June 1998. 
</P>
