<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ethiopia Attains Second Consecutive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chen Cailin)
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's grain
production in 1996/97 has been prospected to reach 11.7 million
tons, representing a 20.6 percent increase over 9.7 million tons
in the previous year, the Crop and Supply Assessment of the
United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO ) and the
World Food Program (WFP ) said in an earlier announcement.
</P>
<P>
This is the second consecutive bumper harvest for Ethiopia
following the excellent 1995/96 season.
</P>
<P>
According to the FAO and WFP, the major increase in grain
production is in Amhara and Oromiya regions, a 24.9 percent and
22.3 percent increases respectively, which account for 80 percent
of the national crop production. The output of Teff, a staple
food for the Ethiopians, increases by 17 percent, while maize by
25 percent, sorghum by 27 percent, wheat 23 percent and barley 8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The bumper crop harvest in the 1995/1996 season has
dramatically improved the food supply in the country. Ethiopia,
with a population of 54 million, is the third largest population
country in Africa. Due to the overgrown population, frequent
natural calamities and civil conflicts, the nation has been among
the few countries which have been severely affected by food
deficit for two decades since the first half of the 1970s.
Following the good harvest in 1995/96, the food gap at the
national level was substantically narrowed. This year's harvest
has further improved the food situation in the country. the
nation has attained food self-sufficiency at the national level
and started exporting grain. The Ethiopian Trade Enterprise has
planned to export 20,000 tons of maize.
</P>
<P>
What makes Ethiopia, a food deficit country in the past 30
years, sufficient in food supply in a very short time. the answer
is that the Ethiopian government has put first priority to the
agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Land under food production has been increased in the past
years. 400,000 farmers have been encouraged to participate in the
agricultural development program and about 400,000 farmers have
been organized under the program. The government supplies farmers
with improved seeds and fertilizers and tries to increase input
for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Peaceful situation and good rains in the last two years have
been described as ''important contirbutors'' to the higher
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
But good rains will not come every year for Ethiopians. They
must raise their ability for combating natural calamities. Not
long before, the government worked out a food security strategy
Under which Ethiopians will put special emphasis on soil and
water conservations, irrigation and tree planting in an attempt
to further promot agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
