<HEADLINE> Chirac, Kohl Ratify Joint Defense Strategic Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 24 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl ratified a text on a new joint
defense strategic concept between the two nations, which stresses
their "indissociable" common security interests, during their
summit last month.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde, a local daily, today published an excerpt of the text
signed by Chirac and Kohl on December 9, 1996 in Nuremberg, which
was translated from its German version.
</P>
<P>
But the French government today refused to comment on the
report, which the newspaper said remained classified documents
until now, said the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The text said that the Franco-German Council of Security and
Defense, co-presided by Chirac and Kohl, "has decided to give a
new impulse to Franco-German cooperation in the field of security
and defense in a European as well as Atlantic perspective."
</P>
<P>
"France and Germany, while being members of the European Union,
the Atlantic Alliance (NATO), and the West European Union (WEU),
are at the center of a network of solidarity," said the text.
</P>
<P>
It said that France and Germany are ready to "open dialogue
over the role of nuclear deterrence within the context of the
European defense policy."
</P>
<P>
"Our two countries are exposed to the same risks.... The need
remains for a territorial defense and a defense of the alliance
because a fundamental change of the conditions of security in
Europe cannot be ruled out," it said.
</P>
<P>
It also said, "All our classic forces, including the forces of
rapid reaction, is in priority at the disposal of the defense of
the allies within the framework of the obligations which follow
the treaties of Brussels (on the WEU) and Washington (on NATO)."
</P>
<P>
Le Monde said that although the text "presents above all a
synthesis of perceptible orientations (adopted by Chirac) over the
past several months," it signals the breaking of some "dogmas"
maintained by the post-war French governments under President
Charles de Gaulle, President Georges Pompidou and President
Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
The text could also meet opposition from some old Gaullist
deputies in the National Assembly and the French Senate, if it was
submitted to them, said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
