<HEADLINE> UK Retail Sales Fall 0.8 Pct in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The suspected weakness of
overall Christmas retail sales in Britain was confirmed Thursday
by official figures, prompting speculation that UK interest rates
would be left unchanged before the general election.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) said that retail sales
fell 0.8 percent in December after a 0.8 percent rise in November,
the biggest drop in 16 months and is much worse than analysts'
expectation of a rise of 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Against a year ago, sales were up only 2.9 percent in December
compared with a year-on-year growth of 3.9 percent in the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
Sales of clothing and footwear fell by an unprecedented 4.6
percent last month in spite of price falls of 0.2 percent, and
were a key factor behind the overall weakness in sales, the ONS
said.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury downplayed the weakness of the figures, saying
that the underlying trend in retail sales remained firmly upward
with sales volumes having risen by 0.9 percent over the past three
months and sales of household goods having been particularly
strong.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, economists said that the fall would help Chancellor
of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke resist Bank of England pressure to
raise base rates from the current 6 percent level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
