<HEADLINE> Economic Growth Slows Down in Ulster in 1996: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in Northern
Ireland slowed down and trailed the rest of Britain as a whole for
the first time this decade, according to a report published
Thursday by the accountants Coopers and Lybrand.
</P>
<P>
The report said that after consistently outperforming the UK in
the 1990s, Ulster's gross domestic product (GDP) grew an estimated
2 percent in 1996, down from 2.5 percent in the previous year.
This compares with an estimated growth rate of 2.25 percent in the
country as a whole last year.
</P>
<P>
The mad cow crisis, slower growth in traditional export markets
and the ending of the Irish Republican Army's (IRA) cease-fire all
contributed to the slowdown.
</P>
<P>
The study pointed out that due to lower demand in key European
markets, destocking by Ulster companies and the impact of the mad
cow crisis on meat processors, the region's manufacturing output
growth fell to 0.3 percent last year, against 4.2 percent in 1995
and 7.2 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, manufacturing employment dropped 1.7 percent
compared with growth of 3 percent in 1995 and 1.9 percent in 1994.
This was the first rise in redundancies since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Tourist numbers suffered a 10 percent fall with the resumption
of para-military violence in the province and the pound's
appreciation also discouraged cross-border shoppers from the Irish
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland, which accounts for 28 percent of the UK's
beef exports, was particularly hard hit by the European Union's
ban on UK beef exports, as cattle prices fell 25 percent due to
lower demand and one in five meat businesses reported cashflow
problems.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on future growth in the province, the report said
that it would have "as much to do with confidence as with
opportunity."
</P>
<P>
"The business community can deliver the exports and the
profits. It is up to the government and the politicians to deliver
the confidence," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
