<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: 21 Countries Certified as Free of Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one countries have been
certified as "being free of dracunculiasis transmission," Hiroshi
Nakajima, director-general of the World Health Organization (WHO),
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
According to a WHO press release, the last dracunculiasis cases
date back to October 1993 in Pakistan, while Iran has not reported
any cases since the middle of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Dracunculiasis, a debilitating parasitic disease also known as
guinea worm disease, has not been reported during this century, or
the conditions needed for its transmission do not exist in the
other 19 countries: Austria, Barbados, Belgium, Brazil, Bulgaria,
Colombia, Cook Islands, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, Finland,
Kiribati, Mongolia, Papua New Guinea, Romania, Singapore, Solomon
Islands, Switzerland, Trinidad and Tobago, and Vanuatu.
</P>
<P>
The above decision is based upon the recommendation of the
International Commission for the Certification of Dracunculiasis
Eradication, a global body established in 1995 under the guidance
of WHO.
</P>
<P>
Although widely prevalent at the beginning of the 20th century,
WHO said, guinea worm disease exists today in dwindling endemic
areas in 16 countries of Africa south of the Sahara, as well as in
India and Yemen in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Between 1992 and 1996, the number of endemic villages around
the world was reduced from 23,000 to 9,900. Many of the endemic
countries today experience only a handful of cases.
</P>
<P>
During 1996 all countries, except for Sudan, experienced a
reduction in the number of indigenous cases, of between 21 percent
and 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
The global campaign against guinea worm began in 1980 within
the context of the International Drinking Water and Sanitation
Decade.
</P>
<P>
WHO said that dracunculiasis may become the first parasitic
disease to be completely eradicated by human effort in the near
future. However, continued international support is essential, WHO
warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
