dollars.
</P>
<P>
The pound's fall will come as a relief to Britain's exporters,
which have been hit by its 13 percent rise against a basket of
currencies since August.
</P>
<P>
Pound began falling when US investors reportedly sold an
estimated 2 billion pounds (3.25 billion dollars) in New York
trading Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
It was also triggered by comments on the same day from
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke, who cited the strong
pound as a reason not to raise base rates from 6 percent after his
latest monthly meeting with Eddie George, governor of the Bank of
England.
</P>
<P>
However, commenting on the currency's fall, Neil MacKinnon,
chief economist at Citibank in London said, "My feeling is that
the big move in sterling is exhausted. Many fund managers are
taking the view that ahead of the election they don't want to add
to their exposure in sterling."
</P>
<P>
In Britain, the pound began to fall just as the Chambers of
Commerce (BCC) declared that nearly every company in the country
had begun to suffer from the high pound restricting
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The BCC urged the government not to raise interest rate. Its
deputy director-general Ian Peters said that resisting a further
rise in interest rates was important if the manufacturing recovery
was not to be "snuffed out."
</P>
<P>
Further rate rises would lead to an even greater appreciation
of sterling, he argued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
