<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Cards Fraud Exposed in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Three Greek men alleged to have
innovated a method of using stolen credit cards to acquire
hundreds of millions of drachmas worth of goods from stores in
Athens were arrested by police today.
</P>
<P>
Police said that it was the first time this particular type of
fraud has been discovered internationally.
</P>
<P>
Working out of a luxury apartment in the seaside suburb of
Glyfade, near the capital, the alleged con men used a special
machine to read, delete and enter data contained in the magnetic
strip on the back of credit cards.
</P>
<P>
According to police, the innovation consists in the fact that
the machine was used to enter false data on the magnetic strip
which bore absolutely no relation to the cardholder's details
appearing in relief on the front of the card.
</P>
<P>
Police said bank ATMS (automatic teller machines) and credit
card machines used in stores were unable to ascertain agreement
between the name on the front of the card with the data contained
in the magnetic strip.
</P>
<P>
The three arrested were identified as Moses Solomos, 49,
Constantine Marantos, 38, and Vassilis Kalaitzidakis, 51. 
</P>
</TEXT>
