<HEADLINE> British Forces to Leave Bosnia with GIs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- British troops based in
Bosnia will leave next year when U.S. forces withdraw, a top
British commander said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Press Club, Field Marshall Sir Peter
Inge, chief of the British defense staff, said, "The understanding
has always been, all in together, all out together."
</P>
<P>
William Cohen, the new U.S. defense secretary, said during his
confirmation hearing on Wednesday that the 8,500 U.S. troops will
be out of Bosnia when Nato's mandate expires in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia was "principally a European problem to be solved", Cohen
said, adding that the Europeans would have to assume the
peacekeeping role after the the U.S. pull out its forces.
</P>
<P>
"I would expect the British government to do exactly the same"
as the U.S. administration, Inge affirmed.
</P>
<P>
Britain, with 5,000 troops in Bosnia, contributes second
largest contingent to the peacekeeping force. 
