<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Calls for Muslim Countries Solidarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan today described the formation of the D-8 Group
which comprises eight developing Muslim countries as a first step
toward the new international order.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan made this remark at a dinner given for the ambassadors
of Muslim countries in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The two-month-old D-8, which groups Turkey, Egypt, Pakistan,
Indonesia, Nigeria, Iran, Bangladesh and Malaysia, was formed at
the suggestion of Erbakan, with an aim to be a vis-a-vis of the
industrialized G-7 bloc.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the banquet, Erbakan said that the old
international system formed during the Cold War was out-of-date,
adding "the G-7 and D-8 will come together to establish a new
world order."
</P>
<P>
He said the D-8 was a positive measure for enhancing
solidarity among Muslim countries in a world currently dominated
by the Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Muslim countries should strengthen their cooperation in the
economic field in order to have a stronger voice in the future new
world system, said Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
The first D-8 foreign ministers meeting was held in Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey, early this month to discuss
political, trade and economic ties among the group members and
did preparatory work for the group's summit scheduled for the
first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the foreign ministers
meeting, Erbakan accused the European Union and the United States
of putting pressure and economic sanctions on Islamic states and
exploiting the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The United States has frowned upon the establishment of the D-8
Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
