<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life in A Camp in Quake-Stricken Parts of Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KASHGAR, January 25 (Xinhua) -- The moon was up and the night
seemed colder, and alongside a military tent, a Uygur farmer was
feeding his two donkeys with a bunch of straw.
</P>
<P>
Memet and his donkeys had survived a terrible earthquake on
Tuesday that measured 6.4 on the Richter Scale, in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region. The tremor claimed at
least 12 lives and injured more than 40.
</P>
<P>
The quake devastated much of Jiashi County in Kashgar, causing
a great deal of property damage, mostly houses and cattle, and was
followed by hundreds of aftershocks, some very strong, over the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
The relief work has gone smoothly, and most who lost their
houses have been moved into tents or makeshift shelters. "For the
first few days after the quake," Memet said, "my neighbors and I
had to spend the night in the bushes. The PLA gave me this tent
last night, and I'm much warmer in it."
</P>
<P>
One who was having a harder time was Niyat Talifu. Wearing a
typical Uygur woolen overcoat, the aged storekeeper lit a fire by
the side of the road to withstand the freezing temperature of the
long night.
</P>
<P>
"My family are in the shelters," he explained, "but I have to
sleep out in the open air all night to keep an eye on the goods
that I retrieved from my grocery store."
</P>
<P>
One surprise was the electric light that could be seen in a
shelter where the farmer Tursun Seyleyi and his family of nine
were living. "We have a small generator of our own," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The shelter was heated by a stove in the center, and the family
seemed to have just finished their dinner, with some bowls of
noodles still sitting on the table. The family had a guest, who
made the small room seem even smaller: an old woman from a
neighboring village.
</P>
<P>
"She lost her house," Seyleyi said, "We all suffered from the
disaster and should share what we have."
</P>
<P>
At the PLA campsite for soldiers and armed police engaged in
rescue and relief, soldiers exhausted from the day's labors were
sound asleep in their tents. Their beds were a thin layer of straw.
</P>
<P>
A relief official said that the soldiers had refused the use of
mats offered by the local government, claiming that they should
not add any burden to the disaster area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
