<HEADLINE> Prominent Thai Aids Poor In South Chinese Ancestral Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Norrarat Tangpakorn, a Thai
national of Chinese ancestry and president of the Thai-Chinese
Journalists' Welfare Fund of Thailand, has donated a sum of
420,000 yuan (50,600 US dollars) to more than 2,800 poor families
in his native Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Tangpakorn is also honorable vice-president of the China
Culture Promotion Association. Since his ancestors originated from
Chaoyang country in eastern Guangdong, he has shown a great deal
of concern for local economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, he called on farmers in the county's
outlying hilly Leiling and Hongchang towns in the winter
cold and offered the money in a hope of helping local folks
have a happy spring festival which falls on February 7.
</P>
<P>
As a charitable act for the good of the ancestral home, he has
donated funds, over the years, through the Thai-Chinese Fund to
helping to improve the mountainous areas' education and build
roads, and bridges. Road conditions are blamed for problems in
mountainous regions. Three-tenths of the villagers are reported to
be living below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Today's donation ceremony was attended by local officials, who
made an inspection tour of two middle schools built at a cost of
some 2.5 million yuan Tangpakorn had donated three years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
