<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Leads in Lower House By-Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary results of the
by-elections for five vacant seats of Nepal's lower house showed
that the communist opposition party has won in two of the five
constituencies, the Election Commission announced today.
</P>
<P>
Candidates from the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) won the most votes in the two constituencies in
Kathmadnu and Sunsari, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
Vote-counting of the by-election in the constituency in West
Nepal's Rupandehi district is still going on, an official of the
Commission told Xinhua by telephone.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, results of the by-elections in other
two constituencies will come out later as vote-counting in the
Baitadi constituency is yet to begin and voting at two polling
stations in the Rautahat constituency has been rescheduled for
Sunday after incidents of polling booth capturing.
</P>
<P>
The by-elections were held Friday in the five constituencies
with a total of 46 candidates running for the five vacant house
seats.
</P>
<P>
By winning the two vacant seats in the House of Representatives
first, the main opposition CPN-UML, which held 87 seats in the
house before the by-elections, would remain to be the largest
party in the parliament unless the ruling Nepali Congress (NC)
party could won all the three vacant seats to be announced later.
</P>
<P>
The NC party, which leads the present three-party coalition
government, currently has 86 MPs in the 205-seat house.  
</P>
</TEXT>
