<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Meets Somali Faction Leader Amid Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 25 (Xinhua) -- EU envoy to Somalia Sigurd
Illing today met with northern Mogadishu faction leader Ali Mahdi
Mohamed over the restoration of the security in the capital
Mogadishu, a day after Friday's renewed fighting near the Dolow
town.
</P>
<P>
The heavy fighting has continued into later Friday evening
between the Ethiopian government forces and the Islamic
fundamentalists group of Al-Itihad Al-Islam around the Surgudud
village, 10 kilometers south of Dolow, said local reports.
</P>
<P>
Heavy artillery rounds, anti-aircraft missiles and heavy
machine guns were exchanged around the village, leaving two
civilians dead and four others wounded, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The clash broke out a day earlier when some 100 armed
Ethiopian ground forces attacked the village of Gawido, 9
kilometers north of the border town of Bulo Hawo.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Dahir Aweys, the military commander of Al-Itihad
fundamentalist group, said his fighters have so far failed to
regain the grounds they lost to the Ethiopian forces late
December outside the Dolow town.
</P>
<P>
Reports from a field radios there said local residents have
fled and evacuated the Gawido and Surgudud villages, mainly for
Luq, some 70 kilometers east of Dolow town, the strongholds of
the Islamic fighters, following the renewed bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian forces did alledgedly not honor the appeals made
by Hussein Mohamed Aidid and other Somali factions for the
unconditional withdrawal of their forces, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
During today's talks, EU envoy Illing expressed his support to
the meeting of Mogadishu's faction leaders on Monday, calling on
Mogadishu's factions to work together on pacifying Somalia and
its capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The two main faction leaders of Mogadishu have pledged their
collaboration with the latest peace initiatives and the
humanitarian assistance by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Factions in Mogadishu were expected to hold negotiations soon
over their political disputes.
</P>
<P>
Illing also met with Hussein Aidid Friday over the
reconciliation and facilitation of the humanitarian deliveries.
</P>
</TEXT>
