<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Plans to Increase Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is planning to
increase its oil production capacity by 500,000 barrels per day
by the year 2000 to reach 3 million barrels, Kuwaiti oil
minister has said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with local Arabic daily Al-Anbaa
published today, Minister Issa Mohammed Al-Mzaidi said Kuwait
has already mapped out special plans to develop the petroleum
sector and increase productivity according to projections of
future rises in global demand for petroleum.
</P>
<P>
The minister said "Kuwait is among a few states in OPEC
(Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries) that have
potentials to meet higher demand in the future as its current
production capacity stands at 2.5 million barrels per day and we
have plans to increase it to 3 million barrels per day by the
year 2000."
</P>
<P>
He said that in order to increase oil output, the concerned
authorities have worked out a plan to dig new wells and build new
oil installations in the northern region, which is rich in
high-quality crude.
</P>
<P>
He said the British Petroleum Company, which struck an
agreement with the state-owned Kuwaiti Oil Company last year,
was conducting some necessary studies on northern oil fields and
giving technical advise to develop them.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has a proven oil reserve of 100 billion barrels. It has
so far been unsuccessful in its calls for a higher quota in OPEC
which set the export quota for Kuwait at 2 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts expect that the world demand for oil, especially
the demand from the Asia-Pacific region, will continue to be
robust over the next decade and beyond and the overall oil needs
in the region will to a large extent be filled by the Middle East
oil.
</P>
<P>
Besides meeting export potentialities, Kuwait is also aimed
at enhancing both at home and abroad its oil refining capacity
which is now at 500,000 barrels per day. Kuwait Petroleum
Corporation (KPC) has set itself a target of building refining
capacity of 400,000 bpd in Asia by the year 2000 through joint
venture operations.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has signed recently a series of agreements with major
international oil companies concerning oil development
techniques, refining and exports.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mzaidi anticipated an increase in oil prices, citing some
reasons such as the biting cold prevailing in the northern
hemisphere of the earth and the oil companies' bids to increase
their reserves.
</P>
<P>
The prices of oil on the international market soared to a
record level of 21 U.S. dollars per barrel during the last
quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The minister played down the negative impact of Iraqi reentry
into the world market on the world oil demand and supply
balance, saying that "the impact of Iraq's return to the oil
market depends on conditions prevailing on the market."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations allows Baghdad to export 2 billion dollars
worth of oil every six months on renewable basis to purchase
food and medical supplies for the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
