<HEADLINE> India Issues New Rules for Investment in Aviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 25 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
issued some new guidelines for investment in aviation which will
make it more difficult for foreign companies to enter the
country's aviation sector, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet meeting on Friday, the government decided that any
proposal related to the entry of foreign airlines into the
domestic sector will have to be referred to the Ministry of Civil
Aviation for clearance.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made when the cabinet was discussing a
controversial joint venture proposal between India's Tata company
and Singapore Airlines which has already been cleared by the
Foreign Investment Promotion Board.
</P>
<P>
The decision has virtually ruled out the Tata-Singapore
Airlines joint venture proposal which was submitted to the cabinet
for final clearance.
</P>
<P>
Civil Aviation Secretary Yogesh Chandra said on Friday that any
Indian national can start a new airline but the question of
foreign airlines' participation must be decided by the Ministry of
Civil Aviation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
