<HEADLINE> Philippine Peace Negotiators to Meet on Recent Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiators of the
Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
are scheduled to meet on Sunday to resolve their recent armed
conflict in the southern Philippines, the Philippine News Agency
said today.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for
political affairs, as saying that representatives of the two sides
would meet in Sultan Kudarat town, Maguindanao province, to
discuss how to settle their clashes in Buldon town, the MILF's
main camp in the province.
</P>
<P>
At least four soldiers and 33 rebels have been killed and
dozens of others on each side wounded in the conflict which
erupted on January 16.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Management Staff Secretary Alexander Aguirre has
said the government would continue to hold peace talks with the
MILF despite its recent stepped-up attacks on government troops.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) which concluded a peace pact with the
government last year, has rejected the government-MNLF peace deal
and demands separate peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Buldon conflict broke out at a time when the government and
the MILF were ironing out trifle differences in preparation for
their future formal peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides' peace negotiators, who held their first round of
low level talks in Sultan Kudarat last month, are scheduled to
meet again on February 25-26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
