<HEADLINE> Beijing Offers Better Postal Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Postal services in the Chinese
capital did 815 million yuan (about 98 million US dollars) worth
of business in 1996, up 17.17 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, 80 more post offices and postal saving units
were opened, bringing the total number to 600.
</P>
<P>
Beijing also opened four more long-distance postal delivery
routes between Beijing and other cities, and 72 more intra-city
postal routes, in a bid to make service more efficient.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of a new postal saving service, the "Green
Card" project, by the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications
last year, 120 post offices have been connected with 60 ATMs
(automatic teller machine), which allow for deposits, withdrawals,
and check-cashing in Beijing and ten other cities, including
Shanghai, Dalian and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,400 new buildings in Beijing were provided postal
services during 1996 and 104 local post offices were
computerized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
