<HEADLINE> Over 11,000 Mozambicans Suffer from Leprosy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 25 (Xinhua) -- As many as 11,642 Mozambicans
suffer from leprosy, listing the country the second and the
ninth leprosy-affected country respectively in Africa and in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The local Noticias newspaper today quoted the Health Ministry
as saying that 6.46 percent of the Mozambicans are lepers and
almost eight among 100,000 Mozambicans have to live in solitude
due to the disease.
</P>
<P>
Northern provinces including Nampula, Cabo Delgado, Niassa and
Manica are more seriously affected by the illness. These regions
are expected to get more help from the World Health Organization
and international donors in the anti-leprosy campaign.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of registered lepers in the southern
African country fell from 18,000 four or five years ago to 1995's
some 12,000, an expert named Alfredo Junior was quoted by the
report as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
