<HEADLINE> Australian Eyes Focus On South China Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 25 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has become the largest trade partner with Australia in
China.
</P>
<P>
Exports from Australia to south China have increased from
580 million Australian dollars to one billion dollars in the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
Now Australia is seeking more investment opportunities in south
China over the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Australian companies are negotiating with officials in
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, on the
construction of key infrastructure projects. These include a
stretch of light-rail and an international airport in Guangzhou,
with total investment exceeding 10 billion yuan (or two billion
Australian dollars).
</P>
<P>
A great potential for economic and trade cooperation exists
between Australia and areas in south China, said Zena Armstrong,
the Australian consul general to Guangzhou, while addressing a
seminar on bilateral economic cooperation in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The consul general revealed that Australia will this year shift
the emphasis of investment to commodity retail and wholesale,
municipal engineering, building material and processing of
foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the goods imported from Australia have then
been re-exported to other Chinese provinces. Australian investment
in Guangdong has totalled some 300 million Australian dollars over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Kate Carnell, a senior Australian official, predicted that
China will be the second largest trade partner of Australia this
year, while the Pearl River Delta will be a springboard for
Australia to expand its development in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
