<HEADLINE> China to Have Biggest Encyclopedia of Literature And Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- China has plans to publish an
encyclopedia of literature and the arts that will perhaps be the
biggest in the world, by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture said today that the
500-million-character, 300-volume book will fully cover the glory
of China's art for the past 5,000 years. It consists of ten
sections that include literature, music, opera, dance, folk tales,
and other literary and artistic genres.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 Chinese researchers and publishers have taken part
in the remarkable program, which began in 1979, and has been
referred to as "China's Cultural Great Wall".
</P>
<P>
The work is unprecedented in Chinese history, or in world
history for that matter, according to State Councillor Li Tieying,
who sent a letter of congratulation to the publisher to mark the
appearance of the first 100 volumes.
</P>
<P>
"It is an honor for the nation and the Chinese people, and an
important contribution to the world, fully demonstrating the
superiority of the socialist system," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China has a long history of compiling large historical and
cultural annals, the most famous being the "Encyclopedia Sinica",
a large series of compiled by hand by scholars under the auspices
of the Qing government during the reign of the Qian Long emperor
(late 18th century). The encyclopedia was a collection of Chinese
classics and traditional philosophy and was so large that it was
stored in more than 6,000 boxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
