<HEADLINE> Hong Kong "Ming Pao" Correspondent Released on Parole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- A correspondent of Hong Kong's
"Ming Pao" newspaper who had been arrested on October 7, 1993 in
China was released on probation today, in accordance with China's
criminal law, according to the Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's
Court.
</P>
<P>
Xi Yang, who was charged with espionage for acquiring state
secrets, and on March 28, 1994, was sentenced by the Beijing
Intermediate People's Court to 12 years in prison, with a deprival
of two years' political rights.
</P>
<P>
Xi responded with a guilty plea and showed a sign of repentance
during his prison term.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with Articles 73 and 74 of the criminal law and Item
No.2 of Article 221 of the criminal procedural law, the Beijing
No.1 Intermediate People's Court released Xi on parole.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that he left Beijing for Hong Kong this
evening. 
</P>
