<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Attracting Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Tianmen City in Central China's
Hubei Province, is increasing its appeal to more investors from
home and abroad by improving its infrastructure and creating a
sound investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Tianmen, reputed for its high degree of education and large
number of natives residing overseas, has invested 300 million yuan
(one U.S. dollar equals to 8.3 Chinese yuan) building a bridge
across the Yangtze River. The bridge links the Wuhan-Yichang,
Wuhan-Jinsha and Yichang-Huangshi highways. The area also has
installed switchboards capable of handling 100,000 telephone
lines, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the officials, the city set up an overseas
investment development zone in 1995, which has so far attracted
19.28 million U.S. dollars worth of foreign funds, and is now home
to 18 businesses.
</P>
<P>
Businesses from a dozen countries and regions, including the
United States, Sweden and the Republic of Korea, regularly visit
the development zone in the hope of finding investment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city generated 14 billion yuan of combined
industrial and agricultural output value.
</P>
<P>
The officials added that the city will try harder to build
itself into a medium-sized city based on textiles, commerce and
trade, culture and tourism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
