<HEADLINE> Hashimoto, Kim Start Talks In Shadow of Comfort Women Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and South Korean President Kim Young Sam began their
summit talks today at the hot springs resort of Beppu in
southwestern Japan.
</P>
<P>
The issue of comfort women was high on the agenda of the two
leaders who aimed to "promote amicable and cooperative relations
between Japan and South Korea."
</P>
<P>
But the meeting was overshadowed by a gaffe by Hashimoto's
chief cabinet secretary and top government spokesman Seiroku
Kajiyama who Friday criticized planned coverage of the issue in
junior high school textbooks.
</P>
<P>
He said it was odd to teach children about Asian women forced
to provide sex for Japanese soldiers before and during World War
II, without also teaching them the social background of an
authorized prostitution system which existed at that time.
</P>
<P>
"Those who are making a fuss over the issue do not know the
authorized prostitution system existed in those days," he said.
He also pointed out that the women got paid when they went to the
front.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama's stance on the comfort women issue is echoed by some
of his Liberal Democratic Party colleagues, who insist that
teenage students should not be taught about it.
</P>
<P>
But the Japanese Education Ministry in June approved the
inclusion of accounts of "comfort women" in all seven authorized
junior high school history textbooks to be used from next April.
</P>
<P>
Historians estimate that between 100,000 and 200,000 women,
mostly from the Korean Peninsula then under Japanese colonial
rule, were forced into sexual slavery for Japanese soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama made the remarks at a regular press conference after
a private fund initiated by the Japanese government paid
compensation to seven South Korean former comfort women earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
South Korea criticized Japan recently for deciding to pay
compensation to former comfort women through the Asian Women's
Fund.
</P>
<P>
It said payment should be made directly by the Japanese
government which announced in August 1993 that in many cases the
women were drafted against their will, "through coaxing, coercion
and so on."
</P>
<P>
The government said that at times, administrative and military
personnel directly took part in the recruitment, noting that
"undeniably, these were acts involving the military authorities of
the day that severely injured the honor and dignity of many women."
</P>
<P>
Apart from the comfort women issue, Hashimoto and Kim were also
expected to emphasize the positive areas of bilateral relations,
which have been frail at best since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirmation of continued coordination between Tokyo and Seoul
toward Democratic People's Republic of Korea was another theme in
their talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
