<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Canal Still Vital for Inland Water Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 25 (Xinhua) -- A millenium after it was
built, China's ancient Grand Canal, which runs from Beijing to the
city of Hangzhou is still carrying boats as the only inland
waterway linking northern and southern China.
</P>
<P>
The northern section, from Beijing down to Jining in east
China's Shandong province, about 700 km, has been closed for
decades to transport because of silting, but the 1000-km section
from Jining southward to Hangzhou remains the "main artery on
water" for the three eastern provinces of Shandong, Jiangsu, and
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Hangzhou, the capital of Zhejiang province, the
canal is responsible for nearly 40 percent of its cargo transport,
and the Tangxi section, in Yuhang county near Hangzhou, handles an
average of 4.8 ships every minute.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of boats and barges use the canal each day and the
three provinces have had a number of dredging projects to better
accommodate water transport. By the end of 1995, the section south
of the Yellow River and north of the Yangtze River was able to
accommodate 1,000-tonnage ships.
</P>
<P>
One renovation project on the 208-km section in southern
Jiangsu, costing 1.5 billion yuan, is now underway, and Zhejiang
has connected the canal with the province's five-river system,
forming a water transport network linking all parts of the
province.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the projects, the water transport volume for Zhejiang
province is expected to exceed 26 million tons in 1996, a record.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang plans to put 640 million yuan (77 million US dollars)
more in repairing bridges, embankments, and the watercourse
itself, while the state has listed renovation of the Grand Canal
as a major project for inland water transport in the period to the
end of the century. 
</P>
