<HEADLINE> Woodies Win Record Eighth Grand Slam Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Australians Todd Woodbridge
and Mark Woodforde won a record eighth Grand Slam men's doubles
title after beating Sebastien Lareau and Alex O'Brien 4-6, 7-5,
7-5, 6-3 in the final of the Australian Open in Melbourne on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Although Woodforde lost his serve four times, the ``Woodies''
broke Lareau six times in the three-hour match.
</P>
<P>
They now have won the Australian title twice, four consecutive
Wimbledons and two U.S. Opens.
</P>
<P>
John McEnroe and Peter Fleming held the previous record of
winning seven men's doubles titles at Grand Slam tournaments since
tennis' open era began in 1968.
</P>
<P>
The victory was worth dlrs 196,000 for the Woodies, who won 12
titles in 13 finals last year. Their major 1996 titles included
Wimbledon, the U.S. Open and an Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Lareau, a Canadian, and O'Brien, an American, shared dlrs
98,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
