<HEADLINE> Anti-Aids Drug Tests Suspended in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Human trials using a new
anti-AIDS drug called "Virodene P058" developed by a group of
South African scientists have been suspended amid mounting
scepticism in the country.
</P>
<P>
The suspension followed a Friday meeting held among AIDS drug
researchers, South Africa's Medicines Control Council (MCC) and
the Ethics Committee of the University of Pretoria's Faculty of
Medicine, the local The Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed on halting treatment with the new drug
until MCC and the Ethics Committee of Pretoria University
complete studies on all available information on the drug's
effects.
</P>
<P>
The scientists in Pretoria University announced at a cabinet
meeting on Wednesday that their latest development of Virodene
P058 had produced far better results for curing AIDS patients
than any existing drugs on the market.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that results of preliminary trial with the drug
on a dozen AIDS patients over the past several months have
suggested a major breakthrough in the fight against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
However, local medical experts expressed doubtfulness towards
the so-called "breakthrough invention."
</P>
<P>
AIDS, an abbreviation of the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome,
is a lethal disease that is usually transmitted through sexual
intercourse, blood transfusion and drug abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
