<HEADLINE> Malaysia, US Expected to Sign Open Sky Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the United
States are expected to finalize their open sky agreement by April,
Malaysian Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik said today.
</P>
<P>
"Discussions on the matter began since the visit of US
Transport Secretary Frederico Pena here last year," Ling, who is
also president of Malaysia Chinese Association, told reporters
after a party meeting in Malacca, according to the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Ling said that further discussions were held from time to time
to eliminate duplication or other problems in formulating the text
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would open up more routes for Malaysia Airlines
(MAS), which currently has six flights a week to Los Angeles, to
the US including more landing rights and destinations, he said.
</P>
<P>
If the agreement was ratified, MAS could fly to the United
States from any other country which has agreement with Malaysia,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would also introduce the concept of open
agreement in aviation which enables an airline to use the services
of another airline to fly to the US, he added.
</P>
<P>
"As an example, MAS can have an open cooperation with any
airline...if the airline does not have a route to the United
States, we can ferry their passengers using MAS aircraft," Ling
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ling said most of the problems faced by MAS had been settled
following a meeting with the pilots, staff and the MAS management.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
