<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: HK Provisional Legislative Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 25 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
held its first meeting here today to elect its president.
</P>
<P>
The election signifies the operation of the 60-member PLC,
which was set up at the fourth meeting of the 400-member Selection
Committee for the First Government of the Hong Kong SAR held in
Shenzhen on December 21 last year.
</P>
<P>
To date, the establishment of the PLC has been endorsed by
various sectors in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Hong Kong people now held that the formation of the
PLC is essential for Hong Kong's smooth transition and the
effective operation of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side has repeatedly reaffirmed that the setting up
of the PLC is a measure it has to adopt after the British side
unilaterally carried out its so-called "Constitutional Package".
</P>
<P>
The "Constitutional Package", which contravened the
Sino-British Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong, the
principle of convergence with the Basic Law and the agreements and
understandings reached between the Chinese and British
governments, has destroyed the "through train".
</P>
<P>
Under the "through train" arrangement, members of Hong Kong's
existing Legislative Council, upon confirmation by the HKSAR
Preparatory Committee, would be members of the first Legislative
Council the HKSAR so long as they are loyal to the HKSAR
government and the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
From April to November 1993, the representatives of the Chinese
and British governments held 17 rounds of talks on the
arrangements for the 1994-95 elections in Hong Kong, which are to
produce the three-tier political structure: the Hong Kong
Legislative Council, urban and regional Councils and district
boards.
</P>
<P>
However, before the representatives of the Chinese and British
governments could reach agreement for the 1994-95 elections in
Hong Kong, the British side unilaterally discontinued the talks at
the 17th round and submitted to the Hong Kong Legislative Council
part of the question under discussion between the two sides, which
directly led to the termination of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, it was the British side's disruption that scuttled
the talks for the 1994-95 electoral arrangements, which in turn,
destroyed the "through train" for Hong Kong's three-tier political
structure.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress (NPC) have made it clear that the Hong
Kong Legislative Council, district boards and municipal councils
elected under Patten's package will stop functioning in mid-1997
when China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The political structure of the HKSAR after July 1, 1997 will be
built in accordance with the relevant decisions of the NPC and the
provisions of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Now that the "through train" has been destroyed because of the
British side's unilateral act, it would be impossible for the
first legislative Council of the HKSAR to be formed at the time
when the HKSAR is established.
</P>
<P>
In that case, lots of legal work stipulated by the Basic Law
and NPC's decisions for the HKSAR's Legislative Council will be
either delayed or suspended, such as the law concerning
application for HKSAR passports and visa issuing, law about
HKSAR's flag and emblem, as well as appointment of the judges of
the Court of Final Appeal and Chief Justice of the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, to avoid a legal vaccum after July 1, 1997, there
should be a provisional legislative council (PLC) to enact
necessary laws and ordinances for the future HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
At the second session held in Beijing On March 24, 1996, the
Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR of the NPC made a decision on
setting up HKSAR's Provisional Legislative Council (PLC).
</P>
<P>
The PLC, which is broadly represented in Hong Kong communities,
consists of 60 members, with 33 people serving at Hong Kong's
existing legislative Council and 11 permanent Hong Kong residents
with no Chinese citizenship or with right of abode in foreign
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
