<HEADLINE> Syrian Capital Suffers from Grave Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Damascus, capital of Syria,
is suffering from serious pollution on account of the immense
increase in the number of minibuses and other vehicles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The total number of minibuses rose to 11,000 last year with
an increase of 4,000 compared with that in 1995, while other
vehicles increased to 194,000 during the correspondent
period, according to official Syrian sources.
</P>
<P>
Additional roads, tunnels, fly-overs and bridges are needed in
the capital city to confront the situation, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Damascus is suffering from traffic problems in view
of the numerous cross-roads and traffic lights, causing jams as
well as rising pollution.
</P>
<P>
The sources call for a scientific and realistic study of the
capital's need for various means of transportation. They also
suggested the opening of tunnels and the building of fly-overs at
cross-roads of busy traffic areas and other locations in the
city, to ease traffic jams and facilitate the flow of vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
