<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus will take measures to restrict the number of
foreign workers on the island and severely punish those who
employ illegal foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Interior Dinos Michaelides said recently that the
number of foreign workers in Cyprus has multiplied six times
from 4,000 in 1987 to 26,000 now, while the illegal foreign
workers are estimated at about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
He announced that from January 1, 1997, those who employ
illegal workers will be punished with up to three years
imprisonment and a fine of 5,000 Cyprus pounds (about 10,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The newly appointed Cyprus Airways (CA) chief Takis
Kyriakides has called for drastic measures to rectify CA's
situation which he described as gloomy, according to local media
reports.
</P>
<P>
Kyriakides told the House Finance Committee that the company
losses for 1996 are expected to reach 6-7 million Cyprus
pounds (about 12-14 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He forecast that the CA will face economic difficulties in
1997 and 1998, with losses expected to exceed 16 million
Cyprus pounds (about 32 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Kyriakides noted that increased costs, competition and
liberalization of air transport are problems that have to be
tackled.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cyprus Stock Exchange (CSE)'s all-share index
fell to a new all-time low in the past few days. On Tuesday the
CSE had recorded what was its lowest closing level since the
official exchange was launched in March last year.
</P>
<P>
It is generally felt that investor's concern about the
political tensions in Cyprus, relating to threats by Turkey over
the island's planned purchase of Russian-made anti-aircraft
missiles, is depressing share prices.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Eighteen new cities, which is expected to absorb 3.5
million citizens and provide 700,000 job opportunities, will be
set up in the new Delta region along the Nile river in Egypt,
local Arabic-language newspaper Al Gomhouria reported today.
</P>
<P>
Investment assigned for the establishment of these cities are
estimated at 33 billion Egyptian pounds (about 9.7 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Fertilizer, cement, mineral water, marble and red bricks
industries will be set up in these cities. 
</P>
