<HEADLINE> DPRK Lashes Out at Japan for Denial of Comfort Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, January 25 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) today accused the Japanese government of
conniving with right-wringers who had attempted to deny the issue
of comfort women.
</P>
<P>
A commentary published by Rodong Sinmun, the mouthpiece of the
ruling Workers' Party of Korea, said the incident of comfort
women, who were sex slaves forced to serve wartime Japanese
troops, was one of the most heinous crimes committed by the
Japanese army during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Any attempt to deny the issue of comfort women is a brazen
denial of history, it said.
</P>
<P>
It criticized some members of the ruling Japanese Liberal
Democratic Party for calling for removing the chapter concerning
comfort women form Japanese history textbooks.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese authorities try to gloss over the crimes at any
cost, bury the historical facts in oblivion and avoid making
compensation," it added.
</P>
<P>
The commentary demanded that the Japanese government honestly
admit all the past crimes including the issue of comfort women,
apologize and compensate for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
