<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Legal Panel's Suggestions Correct: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa cited here today
suggestions by the legal panel of the Preparatory Committee (PC)
to amend some Hong Kong laws as correct, rejecting the saying that
these proposals would lead to a "democracy recession" in the
region.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held after the first meeting of the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC), Tung, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), said that the
British Hong Kong Authorities' unilateral amendments to some
original laws and ordinances contravened the Sino-British Joint
Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong and the principle of
convergence with the Basic Law of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
After reviewing the process of the British Hong Kong
Authorities' actions for drafting Bill of Human Rights Ordinance
and for revising Societies Ordinance and Public Order Ordinance,
he pointed out that the enacted ordinance and the amendments to
the original ordinances by the British Hong Kong government were
breach of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
He said the suggestions set forth by the legal panel of the
Preparatory Committee (PC) were absolutely not "democracy
recession" and that they have nothing to do with the question of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the rights of an individual is important, but the
social order, stability and prosperity are important too.
</P>
<P>
"What we should consider is "how to pursue a balance", he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung voiced his disagreement with some people's viewpoint that
PC's suggestions will undermine the confidence of the foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that as far as he knew from latest surveys,
90 percent of the French businesspeople, 92 percent of the British
businessmen and 95 percent of the American businessmen in Hong
Kong responded positively toward Hong Kong's future, showing their
growing confidence in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the Sino-Joint Declaration on the Question of
Hong Kong and the Basic Law stipulate that after Hong Kong's
handover in the middle of 1997, the existing ordinances and laws
of Hong Kong will basically remain unchanged. And any change in
this regard should be done on the basis of the consensus reached
by the two sides through consultations.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the British side unilaterally amended some of the
original ordinances without any consultations with the Chinese
side. To readdress the issue, the PC legal panel will certainly
raise their recommendations on the subject, he added.
</P>
<P>
Finally, Tung urged all sectors to unite and take into account
the overall interests of Hong Kong at such a critical moment during
the transition period so as to build a bright future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Executed for Producing Counterfeit Spirit in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Five criminals who were found
guilty of producing and selling counterfeit spirit which caused 36
deaths, were executed in Huize County, southwest China's Yunnan
Province, today.
</P>
<P>
Li Rongping and Jiang Hongmei, husband and wife, were farmers
of Liucun Village, Zhehai Town, Huize County, Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
During the period from July 1995 to February 1996, they hired
Yin Guangcai and other people to produce and sell inferior bulk
spirit with edible alcohol. They were fined and their products
were sealed up and confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Although knowing that methyl alcohol was poisonous, the couple
who wanted to seek more profits still purchased 3,300 kilograms of
methyl alcohol from a chemical company on June 15, 1996, and
instructed Yin and others to make over 10,000 kilograms of
spirit. As a result, 33 people died and more than 100 injured
after drinking the spirit.
</P>
<P>
Peng Chuanyun, a farmer of Fanjia Village, Zhehai Town, Huize
County, was fined and his workshop closed down for using edible
alcohol to make inferior spirit in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
On June 15, 1996, Peng purchased 510 kilograms of methyl
alcohol from Li Rongping and produced 2,000 kilograms of spirit
which caused two deaths.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jianwu, a farmer of Luobugu Town, Huize County, bought 82
kilograms of methyl alcohol to made and sell spirit causing one
death.
</P>
<P>
The death penalty was meted out by the Yunnan Provincial Higher
People's Court with the approval of the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily will carry a commentary tomorrow saying that
the move "has sounded a warning against those who are seeking
exorbitant profits by making and peddling fake goods." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
