<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLC Poses No Threat to British HK Government: Rita Fan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Rita Fan, the newly-elected
president of the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC), said here
today that the PLC poses no threat to the governing authority of
Hong Kong, which, at this moment, is with the British Hong Kong
government.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here right after PLC president
election, Rita Fan Hsu Lai-Tai noted the work of the PLC is aimed
at enacting laws that must come into effect on July 1.
</P>
<P>
She said that opposition and in-cooperative attitudes adopted by
the British Hong Kong government toward the PLC are attributed
more to political reasons than to the actual situations.
</P>
<P>
She beat Andrew Wong by 33 votes against 27, at the first meeting
of the PLC held here today.
</P>
<P>
Fan said she herself agreed very much to the necessity and
legal standing of the PLC, adding that she will take up
opportunities to explain them to the public.
</P>
<P>
The power of the PLC to make laws and its legal standing came from
relavant decisions by China's National People's Congress, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The body has been given the duty by the Preparatory Committee for
the Hong Hong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) to look into the
bills to be introduced by the first government of the HKSAR and the
bills which they consider have to be handled by the PLC,
Fan continued.
</P>
<P>
"We only handle those (laws and ordinances) that have to be
handled before the first Legislative Council of the HKSAR is
established," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of the PLC is temporarily scheduled for the late
February, Fan said, and expressed the hope that members of the
Secretariat of the Legislative Council would stay on to serve the PLC.
</P>
<P>
The two special working groups will be set up soon to work on
PLC operational rule and administrative structure, she added.
</P>
<P>
Rita Fan said that she hopes that the PLC will foster a
legislative culture that fits Hong Kong, that is, to deal with
things with a practical, rational, active and constructive
approach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
