<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voter Turnout Gets Record High in Nepal's By-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Voter turnout rates reached a
record high of 73 percent in the lower house by-election held on
Friday at five constituencies in Nepal, the Election Commission
said today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200,000 out of a total of 236,000 eligible voters cast
their ballots on Friday to elect five parliament members to fill
vacant seats in the House of Representatives concluded in the
evening peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The voter turnout rates ranged from 72 to 89 percent in four
constituencies including the one in this capital city while only
45 percent of voters in far-western Nepal's Baitadi constituency
cast their votes mainly due to the heavy snowfall and severe cold
weather there, the commission added.
</P>
<P>
Vote-counting is underway in three of the five constituencies
and the results will be announced later today, an official of the
commission told Xinhua, adding that candidates from main
opposition the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML) are leading in the three constituencies respectively in
Kathmandu as well as Sunsari and Rupandehi districts.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the by-election results in other two
constituencies in Baitadi and Rautahat districts will come out
after one or two days.
</P>
<P>
It was because of the transportation problem in the remote
Baitadi district and the cancellation of voting at two polling
stations in the Rautahat constituency after the opposition's
complaints of polling booth capturing by supporters of main ruling
the Nepali Congress (NC) party.
</P>
<P>
Rescheduled voting at the two Rautadi polling stations will be
held on Sunday, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba's NC party has vowed to win
the by-elections at all the five constituencies while the
opposition CPN-UML said it will win at least three to remain as
the largest party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML currently has 87 MPs while the NC holds 86 seats in
the 205-seat lower house, which has five vacant seats.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
