<HEADLINE> Bangkok's New Airport Plan Still Alive: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has insisted that he had never said that the second
Bangkok international airport at Nong NGU Hao is to be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters on Friday that the new airport project had
been delayed for a long time and it could not be completed by the
year 2000, as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
He said putting Nong NGU Hao airport project on hold and
expanding Bangkok's existing Don Muang International Airport would
suit the country's current economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The country faces current account deficit and the government is
trying to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
The new airport, situated to the Southeast just outside
Bangkok, would cost 100 billion baht (4 billion US dollars) while
expansion of the Don Muang airport would need only one-tenth of
the cost, according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The expansion is expected to be able to cope with increasing
passenger volume for another 10 years, or at least 6-8 years more,
the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
At the cabinet meeting on Tuesday, Chavalit proposed a
postponement of constructing the Nong NGU Hao project because of
its high cost and slow progress. Most ministers at the meeting
went along with the idea but no decision was made.
</P>
<P>
Nong NGU Hao, which means cobra swamp in the Thai language, is
low-lying and the airport would need land refill and a six-km-long
flood prevention wall round the airport site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
