<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Muslim-Croat Federation in Crisis, Zubak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 24 (Xinhua) -- President of the Bosnian
Muslim-Croat Federation Kresimir Zubak today said that the
federation was in crisis and the Bosnian Muslims should be held
responsible for that.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Croatian media, Zubak accused Bosnian
Muslims of violating the agreement the two sides reached under the
auspices of the United State, under which Zubak will be succeeded
by a Croat other than a Muslim.
</P>
<P>
That was why the Croat lawmakers decided Wednesday to boycott
the federation's parliament, Zubak said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton accord which ended the Bosnian war in 1995,
Bosnia-Herzegovina is split into two semi-autonomous entities, the
Serb republic and the Croat-Muslim federation.
</P>
<P>
Muslims and Croats fought each other for 11 months during the
Bosnian war, and in recent weeks tension between the two sides
have heightened over their differences in issues like the share of
power in the federation government.
</P>
<P>
The Croats argued that since Muslim leader Alija Izetbegovic is
the incumbent chairman of the three-person Bosnian presidency, the
federation president should continue to be a Croat so as to keep
balance.
</P>
<P>
But the Muslims quoted the federation's Constitution as saying
that the presidency should be taken by the Croats and Muslims in
turn.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the federation's defense minister, Ante Jelavic,
said that the Croats and Muslims failed to reach an agreement on
the size of the federation army.
</P>
<P>
Jelavic, a Croat, said that the Muslims were trying to keep
more Muslim army so as to maintain a military superiority over the
Croats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
