<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Networks to Boost Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade business
and trade administration will be revolutionized with the
application of computer networks this year, China Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The China International Electronic Commerce Center under the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (Moftec) will
provide China International Electronic Trade networks (CIETNet)
and platforms to promote the introduction of electronic data
interchange (EDI), the system by which computers speak easily and
efficiently to each other under a standardized structure.
</P>
<P>
Moftec Vice-Minister Liu Shanzai said EDI application is
important to upgrading the efficiency of China's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The center will also provide other information, including
Chinese laws and policies concerning trade and investment, and
business information at home and abroad via the networks. This can
sharpen the competitiveness of Chinese exporters and importers and
create opportunities, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Liu said from this year, laws, regulations and documents
concerning foreign trade and economic cooperation that are not
confidential will gradually be entered into CIETNet.
</P>
<P>
The center also will support office computerization of Moftec
and computer work cooperation between Moftec and other government
branches.
</P>
<P>
Liu said to improve trade administration, Moftec's short-term
goal is to use computer networks to distribute and inspect import
and export quota licences, transmit imports and exports
statistics, and supervise export tax repayment.
</P>
<P>
This step is expected to help increase foreign trade
administration efficiency and reduce illegal actions such as using
fake quota licences to gain export opportunities and cheating to
get tax repayment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
