<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO), tin and rubber closed the week mixed.
</P>
<P>
CPO physicals eased this week on follow-through liquidation
activities from last week despite a pick-up in buying interest at
mid-week.
</P>
<P>
The market started bullish on Tuesday following a favorable
crop data released by the private crop forecaster, Ivan Wong whose
latest estimation figures released on Tuesday put up the January
CPO stocks at 730,000 tons and output at about 580,457 tons which
was nine percent down from the official figures of 637,865 tons.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Wong estimated exports for that month at 545,800 tons
compared with 637,899 tons for December which was officially
reported by the Palm Oil Registration and Licensing Authority
(PORLA).
</P>
<P>
However, on Thursday, market prices reversed its recent strong
position to trade lower, as players liquidated their positions on
lack of fresh news and ahead of the Lunar New year and Hari Raya
celebrations next month.
</P>
<P>
But dealers said it was enough to erase the previous gains, as
the market's overall sentiment is still on the negative territory,
which had restricted further upward pressure.
</P>
<P>
January South was traded at 1,330 ringgit (about 532 U.S.
dollars) a ton against the previous week's 1,335 ringgit (about
534 dollars) a ton.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), strong local and foreign
consumer demand and a higher London Metal Exchange (LME) led the
market to close firmer this week in active trading.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market was quite strong with prices adding
nine sen to 14.68 ringgit (about 5.872 dollars) per kg from last
week's close of 14.59 ringgit (about 5.836 dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The bullish LME, which saw base metals prices led by copper,
closing steadier across the board, spilled over to the local
market, which attracted good buying support not only from locals
but also Japanese and European investors.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM was twice unchanged on Monday and Thursday due to the
mixed sentiment on the LME. The week's high was on Tuesday when
the price surged to 14.70 ringgit (about 5.88 dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The week's turnover amounted 494 tons against 582 tons last
week.
</P>
<P>
But again, prices on the Malaysian rubber market extended their
losses this week on a dull market where trading was thin.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market was quiet as both buyers and sellers
continued with their wait-and-see-attitude.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said current prices, now seen as unattractive since
last week, had shifted the attention of most foreign buyers to the
produce in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The bull in the rubber market seemed to have lost its steam
when International February RSS One stopped the week at 302.00 sen
(about 120.8 U.S. cents) per kg, down two sen from last week's
close of 304.00 sen (about 121.6 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20
dropped by 2.50 sen to 297.00 sen (about 118.8 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overseas futures markets showing some positive
signs, the local front failed to receive strength to recover and
to recoup its early losses.
</P>
<P>
However, players were still holding on to market fundamentals,
hoping that there would be "huge" return of buyers after the
Chinese New Year and Moslem's Lesser Bairam (Festival of
Fast-breaking) which fall on February 7 and 9 respectively as they
rushed in to refill their requirements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
