<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Currency Devaluates Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian National Bank
announced Friday that the middle price between the country's
currency lev and the U.S. dollar next Monday will be 813.87 to
one, marking the lev's devaluation by 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The middle price on Friday was 731.71 leva to one dollar,
according to the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday's foreign currency market, the highest buying price
was 830 leva to one dollar and the highest selling price was 880
to one, but on Friday, they were 890 and 930 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The current devaluation has led to a sharp increase in
commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
While confirming that another two banks have gone bankrupt, the
national bank announced that all the commercial banks can decide
the interest rates based on the basic rates.
</P>
<P>
A former Bulgarian finance minister said a runaway inflation is
unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
The currency devaluation took place amidst the political crisis
that has been going on in the country for a month, with all the
parties bargaining with one another on the forming of a new
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
