<HEADLINE> Indonesia Posts Trade Surplus of 5.2 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia posted a trade
surplus of 5.2 billion U.S. dollars in the first 10 months of
1996, a 72 percent increase over the same period of 1995, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus was mainly supported by the increase of
exports and the decrease of imports, Indonesian Minister of
Industry and Trade Tunky Ariwibowo said here Friday after meeting
with President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's import growth last year only registered 4.8
percent, a significant decrease from the previous year's 30.8
percent, today's local press quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The country's export value reached 40.6 billion dollars in the
1996 January-October period, up 10.4 percent over the same period
of 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
The import value reached 35.3 billion dollars in the same
period, an increase of 5.1 percent over 1995. "Imports in the
whole year of 1996 only increased by 4.8 percent from 1995," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Looking at these figures, we can say our economy is improving,
with export growth exceeding import growth," Tunky said.
</P>
<P>
As a comparison, Indonesia's exports increased by 13.39 percent
to 45.5 billion dollars in 1995 from 40 billion dollars a year
before, while imports rose by 22.9 percent to 40.6 billion dollars
from 31.98 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
