<HEADLINE> Talks Between Dhaka, Tribal Rebels Start Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 25 (Xinhua) -- The crucial talks between the
Bangladeshi government and the tribal leaders to end the
long-standing insurgency in Chittagong hill tracts (CHT), will
begin here today.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first meeting in the capital city between the
government and the Parbattya Chattagram Jano Sanghati Samity
(PCJSS), political wing of the CHT rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist Chakma rebels, named as Shanti Bahini, have been
fighting a bush war since 1973 for self-rule of the resource-rich
hill forests in southeast Bangladesh bordering India and Burma.
</P>
<P>
The talks will center round the five-point charter of demands
put forward by the PCJSS during the past two meetings with the
national committee, which was formed by the parliament last month.
</P>
<P>
The main demands include formation of a regional council,
envisaging a self-ruled region in the 14,200 sq. km Chittagong
hill tracts.
</P>
<P>
When contacted, a high level government source expressed his
optimism about reaching an agreement between the government and
the PCJSS during the three-day talks.  
</P>
