<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Chief Cabinet Secretary Raps Coverage in Textbooks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Chief Cabinet Secretary
Seiroku Kajiyama today criticized the planned coverage in junior
high school textbooks of Asian women forced to provide sex for
Japanese soldiers before and during World War II.
</P>
<P>
It is odd teaching them of the comfort women issue, without
teaching the social background of an authorized prostitution
system at that time," Kyodo quoted Kajiyama as telling Japanese
reporters after a regular afternoon press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Those who are making fuss over the comfort women issue do not
know that the authorized prostitution system existed in those
days. There used to be the authorized prostitution system, as an
axiomatic one," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"When they went to the fronts, they got money. Among them,
there were some who were drafted," he added.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that Kajiyama's remarks may have adverse
effect on the meeting between Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and South Korean President Kim Young Sam, which is
scheduled on Saturday in Beppu, a southwestern Japanese spa.
</P>
<P>
His remarks may also provide support to some deputies in the
Diet and scholars who have long been denying the fact of "comfort
women" and insisting on eliminating the comfort women issue from
the textbooks.
</P>
<P>
Historians estimate that between 100,000 and 200,000 women,
mostly from the Korean Peninsula then under Japanese colonial
rule, were forced into sex slavery for Japanese soldiers at front
line brothels run by the Japanese military.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has recently criticized Japan for deciding to pay
solatia to former comfort women through a government-initiated
private fund, saying the compensation to those women should be
made directly by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama's stance on the comfort women question has been echoed
by some of his Liberal Democratic Party colleagues insisting that
teenage students should not be taught about the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry in June approved the inclusion of
accounts of the "comfort women" for all seven authorized junior
high school history textbooks that will be used from next April.
</P>
<P>
In August 1993, after carrying out research on the matter, the
government announced, "In many cases they (the women) were
recruited against their will, through coaxing, coercion and so
on. At times, administrative and military personnel directly took
part in the recruitment."
</P>
<P>
"Undeniably, these were acts involving the military authorities
of the day that severely injured the honor and dignity of many
women," the government said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
