<HEADLINE> South Korean President Leaves for Japan Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam left here today for Japan on a two-day working visit,
during which he will hold summit talks with Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
During the talks to be held on Japan's southern island of
Kyushu, Kim and Hashimoto are expected to exchange views on the
coordination of policies toward the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK), the improvement of relations between Japan and
the DPRK, expanded youth exchanges and future-oriented Seoul-Tokyo
ties, including cooperation in the joint hosting of the 2002 World
Cup soccer finals.
</P>
<P>
Also to be taken up will be issues concerning the trade and
economic cooperation, a fisheries cooperation agreement, exclusive
economic zones and cooperation in the international arena like the
United Nations and the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
However, the two leaders will not discuss the issue of
sovereignty over Tokto Island in the East Sea (Sea of Japan) and
compensation for surviving South Korean "comfort women" who were
forced to serve in military brothels for Japanese servicemen
during World War II, according to South Korean officials.
</P>
<P>
Those issues will instead be taken up in the separate meeting
between South Korean Foreign Minister Yoo Chong-ha and his
Japanese counterpart Yukihiko Ikeda.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Seoul-Tokyo relations have been hurt due
to the remarks made by Japanese officials beautifying Japan's
colonial rule of the Korean Peninsula and Japan's claim for Tokto
Island, where scores of South Korean policemen are stationed.
</P>
<P>
Japan ruled the peninsula as a colony from 1910 until its World
War II defeat in 1945.
</P>
<P>
President Kim's working visit to Kyushu Island has been
arranged in response to Prime Minister Hashimoto's visit to South
Korea's southern island of Cheju in June last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
