<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Unwilling to Pay U.N. Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Republican-dominated
Congress of the United States is planning to cut the U.S.
contribution to the United Nations from 25 percent to 20 percent
and fairly reduce the country's share in peacekeeping spending.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was raised by Benjamin Gilman, chairman of the
House International Relations Committee when meeting with visiting
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Wednesday, according to local
press reports here today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. owes the U.N. 1.3 billion U.S. dollars, bringing the
world body into deep financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, when meeting Annan Thursday, U.S. President Bill
Clinton pledged to pay U.S. arrears to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jesse Helms, the chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, told Annan Thursday that he will introduce
legislation, setting "benchmarks" or conditions for U.N. reform
before any funds could be paid.
</P>
<P>
Annan was made unhappy with Helms' ideas. However, he
recommended that Senate and U.N. staffs work together to identify
reform measures for the international institution.
</P>
<P>
In his remarks to the U.S. National Press Club, Annan said
Friday Washington needs to persuade the other U.N. nations if it
wants to pay less.
</P>
<P>
"The United States can negotiate a lower rate for itself, but
it must persuade other member states first," Annan said, stressing
that this is a challenge for American diplomacy, not the U.N.
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Major powers like Britain and France have frequently demanded
Washington pay its debt to the United Nations unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Annan, a 58-year-old Ghanaian diplomat, arrived in Washington
Wednesday, trying to convince the U.S. administration and congress
to pay their U.N. dues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
