<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Steps up Anti-Corruption Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- China's capital city of Beijing
accepted and heard 1,702 cases involving graft, embezzlement and
bribery last year, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Ma Jianguang, vice-procurator-general of Beijing Municipal
Higher People's Procuratorate, said that Procurators at various
levels have filed charges in 836 of the cases and retrieved 285
million yuan (34.3 million US dollars) for the State and litigants.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the Beijing Municipal People's
Political Consultative Conference, Ma said that 44 officials above
section chief level, including seven senior officials, have been
convicted or are under investigation.
</P>
<P>
Local procuratorates brought suits against 775 people and
approved public security departments arresting 430 alleged
criminals.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows there were 28 serious economic cases in the
city, each involving more than one million yuan (120,480 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"These cases show the success of Beijing's battle against
corruption and the enhanced awareness of the law among the people,
who actively provide valuable clues for solving the cases," Ma
said.
</P>
<P>
Ma attributed the rapid increase of corruption cases to an
imperfect supervisory system for officials and poor management in
some government departments and enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
