<DOCNO> XIE19970125.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provisional Legislative Council Enjoys Support from HK People: Zhou Nan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 25 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Nan, vice-chairman of the
Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), said here today that the establishment of the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong SAR enjoys
support from the majority of the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the first meeting of the PLC, which opened here
this morning, Zhou said that the PLC has been established on a
sound legal basis with its legal status and power originated from
relevant decisions of the Chinese National People's Congress
(NPC) and the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the PLC has no inheritance relations with the
existing Legislative Council under the rule of the British Hong Kong
Authorities.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, also director of Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch,
said that the sole and important job for the PLC members at the
meeting is to elect the President of PLC.
</P>
<P>
One month ago, the Selection Committee for the First Government
of the Hong Kong SAR elected 60 members to form the PLC which is
to shoulder historical tasks in one year after the mid-1997
handover.
</P>
<P>
He said that high efficiency in accomplishing its heavy tasks
calls for the PLC to choose a competent leader.
</P>
<P>
Zhou expressed the belief that the PLC members will take into
account Hong Kong's overall interests and take a responsible
attitude towards the election of the PLC president.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the establishment of the PLC, Zhou said as the
British side destroyed the "through train" arrangement, it is
impossible to form the first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong
SAR under the British rule.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, there is much legislative work to be done in
the transitional period according to the Basic Law and the NPC's
decisions.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid a legal vacuum and to ensure Hong Kong's
smooth transition and normal operation of the Hong Kong SAR, the
Preparatory Committee decided to establish the PLC before the
formation of first Legislative Council in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou quoted Qian Qichen, chairman of the Preparatory Committee,
as saying at the fourth meeting of the Selection Committee held in
Shenzhen one month ago that the PLC will enact the laws
indispensable to the Hong Kong SAR and will not replace the
existing HK Legislative Council, that the laws passed by the PLC
will not go into effect till July 1, 1997, and that the PLC will
not in any way affect the rule of the Britain in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that like the first Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
SAR, the PLC members will take oath of office on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"But we can not say that before their taking oath of office,
the PLC members are not able to perform some necessary duties and
make preparations for legislation of the Hong Kong SAR," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the first Chief Executive of the Hong Kong SAR
has the right to form the administrative bodies and Executive
Council of the Hong Kong SAR before July 1, 1997, the PLC members
also have the right to do their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
