<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Merapi Volcano Spews Heat Clouds Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jakarta, January 25 (Xinhua) -- after two days of insignificant
activity, Mt. Merapi, one of Indonesia's most active volcanoes,
again began spewing hot clouds early Friday.
</P>
<P>
Volcanologists stationed at the Laliurang monitoring post said
Mt. Merapi spewed heat clouds 13 times between 1:00 a.m. and 3:00
a.m. Friday, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The heat clouds moved 3,500 meters toward the Krasak river in
the southwestern part of the volcano and, although they have not
reached nearby residential areas, locals have been put on alert.
</P>
<P>
The 2,968 meter high volcano, located on the border of Central
Java and Yogyakarta, erupted on January 17, forcing the evacuation
of some 15,000 villagers.
</P>
<P>
Most of the evacuees had returned home in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, head of the Yogyakarta Volcanology Office, Mas Atje
Purbawinata, said a dome of lava continues to develop in Mt.
Merapi.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have lowered the danger status from 'alert' to
'stand-by' following the volcano's declining activities since
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The volcano could worsen any time, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The last major eruption of Merapi occurred in 1994, sending
massive heat clouds all over the area, killing 69 people and
leaving 5,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's 17,500 islands are dotted by about 500 volcanoes,
127 of which are active and make up the pacific rim of fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
