<P>
BEIJING, January 25 (Xinhua) -- China will exert more efforts
on protecting wildlife, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Forestry Wang Zhibao has pledged to raise
public awareness, improve the legal system, channel more funds and
work to develop infrastructures suitable for the perpetuation of
the nation's wildlife.
</P>
<P>
These endeavors are expected to confront the problems that
undermine wildlife protection, which include shrinking wetlands
and forestry areas due to land reclamation, rampant poaching and
trafficking of protected species in some areas.
</P>
<P>
China will also incorporate harsher punishments in the Penalty
Law, which is under revision and expected to become effective this
year. The new law will hopefully succeed in curtailing many of
these illegal activities, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
With the most recent issue of wild plant protection
regulations, the ministry is now equipped with a legal and
administrative system to oversee wildlife protection.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also try to attract more funds from domestic
and international organizations to ease the fund shortage.
</P>
<P>
It is willing to supply a few giant pandas for international
research, promote protection of worldwide and assist in the urgent
protection of some other 1,000 pandas living in the wild, the
vice-minister said.
</P>
<P>
Fund shortages have vetoed the start of the Habitat
Conservation Project for the giant panda, which needs at least 600
million yuan (72.3 million US dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
