<HEADLINE> Frankfort Customs Reports Unprecedented Seizure of Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Airport customs in Frankfort
reported the seizure of three tons of narcotics in 1996,
surpassing any of the previous years.
</P>
<P>
More than 830 kilograms of cocaine were captured by the
Frankfort airport customs, which accounted for 60 percent of the
total of such drug seized throughout Germany.
</P>
<P>
Hans Engelhardt, the official in charge of the customs, said
drug-smuggling rings had turned the city on the Maine River into
the third largest narcotics shipping port in Europe, only after
Amsterdam, Holland and Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
He added that the volume of cocaine smuggled from South America
kept increasing.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, officials of the customs detected 1.3
tons of marijuana to be transported to Holland via Frankfort.
Following the case down, they cracked down on a drug-smuggling
ring with the coordination of Dutch police and customs.
</P>
<P>
Karl Reider, another customs official, attributed the success
in the crackdown on drug smuggling to international coordination.
</P>
</TEXT>
