<HEADLINE> Central Asian Countries to Further Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A conference attended by
chiefs of staff from Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan ended
here Friday with decisions to further develop military cooperation
among the three Central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day conference, the military heads mainly talked
about the issue of setting up a committee of the three chiefs of
staff, the Kazakhstan news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They adopted a plan to hold a joint military exercise.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs of staff also initialed three agreements on future
military cooperation, which will be formally signed by their
defense ministers in February in the Uzbekistan Capital of
Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
The idea to establish the military committee was agreed on by
the presidents of the three countries on January 10 at the Kyrgyz
Capital of Bishkek. 
</P>
