<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- The meeting of Latin American nuclear authorities
will be held in Cuba March 3 to 7 sponsored by the Atomic Energy
International Organization and will have the intention of
promoting ways of collaboration between the member nations of
regional cooperative agreements for the promotion of nuclear
sciences and technologies.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban Nuclear Energy Agency (ASEN) informed that the
meeting, to be attended by representatives of 18 countries, among
them Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Mexico, will hear discussions on
policies and procedures, and the study of a plan for regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The Chilean Treasury misses each year between 3
billion and 3.5 billion dollars because of tax evasion, almost a
fifth of the total exports of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean Internal Revenue Service informed that it has been
improving its systems of control of taxpayers, and at the same
time maintaining a high level of efficiency to reduce tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- 291,000 tourists have entered Uruguay during the
first 24 days of the year, a 16 percent increase compared to a
similar period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguayan Migration National Direction said most of the
travelers who enter this country through the various centers of
control are Argentines, followed far away by Brazilians, Chileans,
and Paraguayans.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian government hired the Bank of
Boston to issue Eurobonds at a fixed rate for a minimum of 250
million dollars and a top of 300 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The issue is part of the effort of the Panamanian government
which seeks to establish a point of reference that will serve as
an entrance to the capital markets for the public sector and for
the private sector. The product of the emission will be used to
reduce the foreign debt of the country.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuba will have technical assistance worth 1.3 million
dollars from the Atomic Energy Interantional Organization for the
implementation of eight new projects and the continution of other
five during 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Among those projects are the development of radio pharmaceutic
products for therapy, the use of nuclear techniques for the study
of the pollution of the Almendares River, as well as the followup
of the theme of vegetal nutrition through research of the
performance of the fertilizers most used in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
