<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Pequiven company, a branch of the state company
Petroleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), produced last year 454,438 metric
tons of ethylene, a 17.6 percent increase over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Ethylene production in the month of December of last year was
46,615 tons, a 7.5 percent increase compared to May. Ethylene is a
fundamental raw material for the production of plastic resins.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- "Elektra," a chain of 455 department stores in 99
cities of Mexico, plans to establish this year 35 stores in
Central America and the Caribbean to sell electrical home
appliances.
</P>
<P>
"Elektra" will establish itself in Guatemala and El Salvador in
the first half of 1997 with a 30 million dollar investment, and
during the second half of the year in Honduras, Nicaragua, and
Costa Rica, and also in the Dominican Republic, informed the local
press.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican steel industry will maintain the
same growth rhythm of last year, when steel production reached
13,000 tons, and this year could grow 7 percent, as forecast by
the Ixe financial group.
</P>
<P>
An analysis made by the Ixe group shows that investments in
1997 will be over 1 billion dollars, directed mainly to
consolidate the technological advance of the sector.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican government will reduce this year
its expenses by 65.6 million dollars, as part of the measures to
reduce its budget deficit and the foreign debt, announced Finance
Minister Francisco de Paula Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
The reduction will affect those sectors the government can
control, such as additional expenses in the ministries,
superfluous expenses in travel expenses, receptions,
transportation, representation expenses, and publicity in the
ministries.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The volume of revenue from brazilian exports of
soybeans and its by-products reached 4.4 billion dollars in 1996,
a 15.9 percent increase over the 3.8 billion dollars earned in
1995, informed the Breazilian Agriculture Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The income from the export of soybean meal, the main product of
soybeans, increased 35.2 percent, when it went from 2 billion
dollars in 1995 to 2.7 billion dollars in 1996, but the exports of
the product diminished 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The value of the export of soybeans in grain grew last year
31.2 percent over 1995. enditem


