<HEADLINE> New York City Outdoing Suburbs in Job Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- For the first time since 1980,
New York City outdid its entire suburbs last year in making new
jobs, according to a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the United States Bureau of Labor as saying
that of the 70,000 net new private jobs added in the 27-county
region, 37,000 were in the five boroughs of New York, to that the
city has never come close in the last 17 years. Through the boom
years for job creation from 1979 to 1988, the city accounted for
only about one quarter of the one million new jobs created in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the changing balance between the growth
rates of city and suburbs to the slowed growth in suburban job
creation. New York City's private job base rose 1.3 percent in
1996, while growth in the suburban job base rose only 0.8 percent,
according to Federal figures.
</P>
<P>
The report listed two reasons for the faster job growth in the
city. One is an increasing number of international produced film
projects which found New York to be a convenient halfway point
between Hollywood and Europe for both financing and production.
6,600 new jobs were created in areas like motion picture
production. Another is the security industry, which, buoyed by the
bull market for stocks, fueled much of the city's job creation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
