<HEADLINE> European Shares Dive Sharply on Weak Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
retreated from Thursday's record close and all ended sharply lower
Friday, depressed by another weak performance on the Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's sharp downturn dragged the FTSE 100 index on the
London market lower in sympathy, leaving the index 52.7 points
down at 4,218.8 by the time of close after finishing at a new
record high Thursday, but still a rise of 11.1 points on last
week.
</P>
<P>
London was also unsettled by a warning from one of Britain's
major supermarket chains J. Sainsbury that 1996 profits would be
well below analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that profit-taking following Thursday's record
close compounded the downtrend.
</P>
<P>
On the Frankfurt market, which ended before Wall Street opened,
an overnight fall of the Dow and a depressed bond market helped
keep shares lower, with the DAX-30 index ending the week below the
3,000-point level, down 35.22 at 2,998.24, dropping 3.13 points on
the week.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment in Paris also reversed today as the market
followed the general trend lower, hit by Wall Street's decline and
weaker bonds, with the CAC-40 index finishing the session 30.91
points down at 2,430.34, gaining 5.24 points on last Friday.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended 52.7
points down at 4,218.8. In Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index closed
35.22 points lower at 2,998.24. The Paris CAC-40 index finished
down 30.91 at 2,430.34. 
</P>
</TEXT>
