<HEADLINE> 10 Tons of Narcotic Drugs Destroyed in Tanzania's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
destroyed about 10 tons of narcotic drugs, which were impounded
at the Dar Es Salaam port last year, at Wazo Hill Cement Factory
in the city today.
</P>
<P>
A 40-foot container containing the contraband was opened and
burnt under tight security by armed Field Force Unit (FFU)
men.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Criminal Investigations (DCI), Adadi Rajabu,
said the police has offered a special reward to any person who
gives a tip for having the three suspects of drug traffickers
arrested.
</P>
<P>
He said the three suspects are two Tanzanians named Andrew
Mtegeki (a private pilot) and Abduh Awadhi respectively and a
South African identified as Paulos Palma.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian police had arrested Awadhi on charge of drug
smuggling and had him sentenced to three years imprisonment, but
finally Awadhi won an appeal and was set free.
</P>
<P>
"Any person who will give us the right information to find the
suspects will get a huge reward but if one will be found to have
been concealing, (he) shall be held accountable," Rajabu said.
</P>
<P>
The contraband was intercepted by police at Dar es Salaam port
last February. It was shipped in 150 bags of tea from Nakonde,
Zambia, to Ukraine aboard MV Afro Asia Star.
</P>
<P>
The origin of the drug was still unknown. But some of the
papers in which the narcotic drugs were wrapped read, "Fancy
Cutchup, Made in USA for exclusive use by MC Donald
Restraunts".
</P>
<P>
The Zambian police have found 7.97 tons of cannabis resin
worth 30 billion Tanzania Shillings (about 50 million U.S.
Dollars) and 1.94 tons of heroin valued at 20 billion T.Shs.
(about 33 million Dollars) since last February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
