<HEADLINE> Albright Stresses Importance on NATO Enlargement, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. new Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said today that NATO's enlargement was
essential and keeping good relationship with Russia is paramount
to U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that it is essential to enlarge NATO," Albright
said at her first news conference as secretary. "We understand
that the Russians have some problems with that. But what is clear
is that both countries are committed to working this situation out
and developing mutual understanding based on our national
interests."
</P>
<P>
She stressed the importance of U.S.-Russian relations. "I think
it is very important as we look at our agenda over the next years
to understand that our relationship with Russia, a good
relationship with the Russian Federation is paramount to our
interests," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said good relations between the two countries were also
important to the international community.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its alliance have met Russia's opposition
to NATO's eastern-ward expansion, as Russia sees the expansion as a
threat to its national security.
</P>
<P>
The United States has repeatedly stated that NATO's plan of
enlargement would not be stopped by any outside power, but at the
same time, the U.S. and its alliance are trying to calm the
Russians and talk the latter into accepting the idea.
</P>
<P>
Albright said a meeting set for February in Washington between
high-level U.S. and Russian officials would go forward, despite
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's recent health problems.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Clinton were scheduled to hold a summit meeting in
March. NATO's enlargement is expected as one of the top topics at
the meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
